    "body": "@Legend-Master Hmm - for what it's worth, in my own project the signing flow does work end-to-end with this fork (on `windows-latest` via GitHub Actions).\r\n\r\nI also dug into the NSIS source, and as far as I can tell, the current PR shouldn't actually be able to hit the conflict path. Sharing my trace below.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe `Plugin command ... conflicts with a plugin in another directory!` error only fires when the DLL name is in makensis' internal `m_dllname_conflicts` set.\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/NSIS-Dev/nsis/blob/d20198c805a603b2e6359458152987f49f3637cd/Source/script.cpp#L5079-L5083\r\nhttps://github.com/NSIS-Dev/nsis/blob/d20198c805a603b2e6359458152987f49f3637cd/Source/Plugins.cpp#L246\r\n\r\nThe only place that inserts into that set is `GetExports` in `Plugins.cpp`,\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/NSIS-Dev/nsis/blob/d20198c805a603b2e6359458152987f49f3637cd/Source/Plugins.cpp#L151\r\n\r\nand its condition is `DllHasDataHandle(dllName) == true` - i.e. that DLL has already been assigned a data handle from a previous plugin command. The handle itself only gets set by `SetDllDataHandle`, which is only called from `TOK__PLUGINCOMMAND` processing:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/NSIS-Dev/nsis/blob/d20198c805a603b2e6359458152987f49f3637cd/Source/script.cpp#L5117\r\n\r\nSo the necessary order for the conflict error to fire is **\"a plugin call (e.g. `System::Call`) is processed first → then a `!addplugindir` for a directory containing the same DLL is parsed\"**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nIf I walk through the `installer.nsi` this PR generates and watch the order in which `!addplugindir` and `System::Call` actually appear:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/koki-develop/tauri/blob/bea3d5f9aa08ab6887c6e9fbea5d57636757db1a/crates/tauri-bundler/src/bundle/windows/nsis/installer.nsi#L16-L29\r\n\r\n1. None of the `!include`s above the new `!addplugindir` emit anything on their own - the `System::Call`s inside them all live within `!macro` definitions, which are just stored as templates until they get expanded by `${MacroName}` or `!insertmacro`. The same applies to tauri's own `utils.nsh` / `FileAssociation.nsh`:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/koki-develop/tauri/blob/bea3d5f9aa08ab6887c6e9fbea5d57636757db1a/crates/tauri-bundler/src/bundle/windows/nsis/utils.nsh#L22-L71\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/koki-develop/tauri/blob/bea3d5f9aa08ab6887c6e9fbea5d57636757db1a/crates/tauri-bundler/src/bundle/windows/nsis/FileAssociation.nsh#L131-L135\r\n\r\n2. The new `!addplugindir` runs - at this point no DLL has a data handle yet, so nothing gets added to `m_dllname_conflicts`.\r\n\r\n3. `${StrCase}` is expanded, and that's where the very first `System::Call` actually appears in the script (this is also when `System`'s data handle gets set):\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/NSIS-Dev/nsis/blob/d20198c805a603b2e6359458152987f49f3637cd/Include/StrFunc.nsh#L158-L201\r\n\r\n4. After that, the only other `!addplugindir` in the script is the existing one at L94 (`${ADDITIONALPLUGINSPATH}`). That directory only contains `nsis_tauri_utils.dll`, and the only DLL with a data handle so far is `System` (not `nsis_tauri_utils`), so this one doesn't insert into `m_dllname_conflicts` either.\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/koki-develop/tauri/blob/bea3d5f9aa08ab6887c6e9fbea5d57636757db1a/crates/tauri-bundler/src/bundle/windows/nsis/installer.nsi#L93-L94\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/koki-develop/tauri/blob/bea3d5f9aa08ab6887c6e9fbea5d57636757db1a/crates/tauri-bundler/src/bundle/windows/nsis/mod.rs#L46-L61\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSo as far as I can see, there's no point in the generated `installer.nsi` where the conflict condition would actually be satisfied.\r\n\r\nIf possible, could you share the few log lines right before `Plugin command System::Call conflicts ...` fires (ideally with the `.nsi:NNN` line reference)? That'd help pinpoint which `System::Call` is the one triggering it. Also - are you using a custom template by any chance?",
